# Code Quality (Team-Wide)

Derived from the team code-quality rules. Applies to all AI-assisted work in this repository.

## Verification

- Verify information before presenting it. Do not assume, guess, or speculate without clear evidence from the codebase or context.

## How to apply changes

- When changing multiple files, prefer a clear file-by-file flow so the user can review each step.
- For a single file, prefer one coherent edit (one patch) rather than many tiny sequential instructions for the same file.
- Implement only what was explicitly requested; do not add unrelated features, refactors, or “while we are here” changes.
- If nothing needs changing, do not suggest cosmetic updates to files.

## Communication

- Do not use apologies.
- Do not write meta-comments in code or docs about whether you “understand” the task.

## Style and scope of edits

- Do not suggest whitespace-, indentation-, or spacing-only changes unless the user asked for formatting.
- Preserve existing behavior and structure outside the requested scope; do not remove or alter unrelated code.

## Working with the user

- Do not ask the user to re-confirm information they already provided in the conversation or that is visible in context.
- Do not ask the user to manually verify that something is implemented when the result is already visible in the shared context.

## Files and paths

- Reference real paths in this repo (for example `docs/architecture.md`). Do not use placeholder names like `x.md`.
- Prefer reading actual workspace files over relying on vague memory of earlier runs.

## Explanations

- Do not dump or narrate the current implementation in full unless the user asks to see or discuss it.

## Summaries

- Unless the user asks for a recap, keep closing notes short; avoid repeating a full line-by-line list of edits.
